e":"1290–Overleden","1290–1344":"1290–1344","1316–1407":"1316–1407","1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–Female":"1278–Overleden","1316":"1316","1278":"1278","1344":"1344","Abt 1320":"circa 1320","1298":"1298","1407":"1407","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Daresbury, , Cheshire, England":"Daresbury, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Daresbury, Cheshire, England":"Daresbury, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheshire, , England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1298–":"1298–Deceased","1298–Female":"1298–Deceased","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","1290–1344":"1290–1344","1316–1407":"1316–1407","1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–Female":"1278–Deceased","1316":"1316","1278":"1278","1344":"1344","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1298":"1298","1407":"1407","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Daresbury, , Cheshire, England":"Daresbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Daresbury, Cheshire, England":"Daresbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, , England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Agden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name, either from the district of Arden in Warwickshire or from Arden in Bredbury (Cheshire). The first placename is thought to be derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘high place’, cognate with <i>Ardennes</i>, the name of a forested region on the borders between northeastern France and eastern Belgium. The second derives from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>worthign</i> ‘enclosed settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Harden","meanings":["English: variant of   Arden   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>.","English: habitational name, either from Haredene Wood in East Tisbury (Wiltshire), or from Haredon (in Ugborough, Devon). The first placename probably derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. The second is from Old English <i>hara</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hare hill’.","English: variant of   Harding  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Agden was born in 1298, in Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Agden, was 18 and her mother, Mary, was 20. She married Sir John Daniell about 1320, in Daresbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She died in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1298–":"1298–Surnud","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1290–1344":"1290–1344","1316–1407":"1316–1407","1280–1298":"1280–1298","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1316":"1316","1278":"1278","1344":"1344","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1298":"1298","1407":"1407","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Daresbury, , Cheshire, England":"Daresbury, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Daresbury, Cheshire, England"